Space Trajectory Analysis “CAMBRIAN” User's Manual, February 2011

 

INTRODUCTION

About STA

STA stands for “Space Trajectory Analysis”.

 

The STA web site can be found at the following URL: http://sta.estec.esa.int

 

The objectives of STA are threefold: first, to build an education environment in areas like astrodynamics, space sciences, mathematics, and informatics where teachers and students can interact towards Master, PhD, and postdoctoral degrees. Second, to promote the exchange of technical ideas, and raise knowledge and competence in these areas at University level. Last to provide a software suite for the purposes of research. In this sense, STA is conceived as test bed for the testing, verification and validation of new ideas, technologies, and techniques.

 

Conceived as a education and research tool to support the analysis phase of a space mission, STA is able to visualise a wide range of space trajectories. These include among others re-entry, descent and landing trajectories, orbits around planets and moons, etc.

 

The STA development is open source and it is based on the state of the art astrodynamics routines that are grouped into modules. The modules are programmed using the C++ language.

The STA project allows a strong link among applied mathematics, space engineering, and informatics disciplines by reinforcing the academic community with requirements and needs coming from space agencies and industry real needs and missions.

STA Users and User's types

The target user community of STA is listed as follows:

* Space Engineering Student: The student user is in the process of obtaining the knowledge on astrodynamics and orbital mechanics that is necessary to fully understand the models and properties of the software.

* Space Engineering Teacher: interested in the use of STA in the classroom as a tool for education. His/her key objective is to use the tool as a mean to explain the principles and applications of flight dynamics, orbital analysis, applied mathematics, informatics, etc.

* Astrodynamics Specialist: The Astrodynamics Engineer user has knowledge in the area of astrodynamics and orbital mechanics.

* Mathematical analyst: utilises the STA software suite as a test bench to proof-concept new ideas and algorithms in the area of the applied mathematics for space problems (propagators, integrators, interpolators, etc).

 

STA BINARIES

The STA versioning system names are taken from the Earth geological EONS. “ARCHEAN” is the first version. “HADEAN” corresponds to version 2. “CAMBRIAN” corresponds to version 3.  Intermediate versions may be released every Quartal in between major releases. The present user's manual explains the features available for the CAMBRIAN version of STA only.

 

STA comes in three flavors: Windows, Linux and MAC OS X

 

 

Identical functionality is provided in all operating systems supported. The widgets are operating system native and provide the user the same look and feel of the rest of the applications of the operating system used.

 

Requirements to run STA

STA has been tested to work on the following variants of the 3 operating system families supported:

* Windows XP, Windows VISTA, and Windows 7

* Linux Ubuntu 10, Linux OpenSUSE 11.2, Linux Fedora 10, Linux OpenSUSE 11.2, Ubuntu 9.1, Linux Mint KDE 7 Gloria

* MAC OS X 10.5, MAC OS X 10.6

 

All versions of STA require that the user has OpenGL installed. Windows and MAC OSX  come with OpenGL drivers pre-installed. For linux, more and more distributions are shipping with OpenGL, so if you’ve recently installed or re-installed Linux, there’s a good chance that you already have a working OpenGL configuration.

 

In general, to run STA, the computer should have a CPU (processor) that has a speed of at least 1200 million cycles per second (1.2 GHz).  Typically, computers bought new within the last 4 years have adequate CPU speeds.  If your computer is more than 4 years STA 3D visuals may run slowly or not run at all.

 

The 3D visuals of STA require an OpenGL compatible graphical card to run the 3D visualisation graphics. It is required to have a computer with a minimum of 128 Mb RAM and 500 Mb hard disk.

STA CAMBRIAN is a 32-bit application. However, STA CAMBRIAN will run on 64-bits operating systems. Support for 64-bits is currently the target of the CAMBRIAN version.

 

STA CAMBRIAN only runs on Intel-i386 compatible computers. At this moment, STA has not been compiled on PPC, or Solaris computers.

 

 

The web site of STA allows the download of both the source code and the current binaries.

 

The STA binary install packages allow the user to perform basic installations quickly and without hassle. Just run the installer package and follow its instructions.

 

STA Source

The installation of the STA from source code requires the use of a SVN (subversion) client in the user's machine and a suitable compiler to compile the code:

In Windows it is recommended to use TortoiseSVN.

In Linux distributions have SVN client install by default.

MAC OS X 10.4,  10.5, and 10.6 has a command line SVN client install by default.

 

To download the source, from the SVN it will be just required to type in the following command in the desired folder that will accommodate the files:

 

svn co https://svn.forge.osor.eu/svn/sta/trunk sta

 

 

Once the source code has been checked out of the SVN STA repository, the user needs to compile it. STA uses Qt technology to allow fast compilation in the three operating system families supported. The Qt open source edition can be downloaded from the Qt web site. Qt will install in the three families of operating system supported by STA.

 

If the installation of Qt was successful, the user needs to run a simple command to compile the entire source code. The command has to be issued in the folder “sta-src” of the STA source code hierarchy:

 

qmake -config release; make

 

 

Downloading and installing SPICE NASA files

STA includes out of the box the JPL DE405 ephemeris to compute the position and velocity of the major Solar system bodies. However, for more accuracy and total coverage of all Solar System bodies, the user can install manually the NASA SPICE kernel files.

 

SPICE is an NASA information system to assist in planning and interpreting tasks associated with planetary missions.

 

More information about this project can be find visiting its web site: http://naif.jpl.nasa.gov/naif

 

SPICE kernels are a standard way of delivering high accuracy ephemeris data. SPICE kernels can be used as the ephemeris instead of the default JPL DE405 ephemeris included in STA.

 

To enable SPICE in STA, files have to be downloaded and placed in the appropriate folders of the STA installation depending on the operating system used. The outer planet ephemeris files also contain positions of the system barycenters.

 

The SPICE files contents and respective URL's are as follows:

 

leap seconds kernel (very small text file): naif0009.tls

ftp://naif.jpl.nasa.gov/pub/naif/generic_kernels/lsk/naif0009.tls

 

planetary constants kernel: pck00009.tpc

ftp://naif.jpl.nasa.gov/pub/naif/generic_kernels/pck/pck00009.tpc

 

DE 421, the latest planetary ephemeris from JPL: de421.bsp

ftp://naif.jpl.nasa.gov/pub/naif/generic_kernels/spk/planets/de421.bsp

 

Jupiter system ephemeris for Amalthea, Thebe and Galilean satellites: jup230l.bsp.

ftp://naif.jpl.nasa.gov/pub/naif/generic_kernels/spk/satellites/jup230l.bsp

 

Saturn system ephemeris for Mimas, Enceladus, Tethys, Dione, Rhea, Titan, Hyperion, Iapetus, Phoebe + Tethys & Dione co-orbital satellites: sat317.bsp

ftp://naif.jpl.nasa.gov/pub/naif/generic_kernels/spk/satellites/sat317.bsp

 

Uranus system ephemeris for Miranda, Ariel, Umbriel, Titania, Oberon: ura083.bsp

ftp://naif.jpl.nasa.gov/pub/naif/generic_kernels/spk/satellites/ura083.bsp

 

Neptune system ephemeris for Triton, Nereid, Proteus: nep081.bsp

ftp://naif.jpl.nasa.gov/pub/naif/generic_kernels/spk/satellites/nep081.bsp

 

Pluto system ephemeris for Charon, Nix, Hydra: plu017xl.bsp

ftp://naif.jpl.nasa.gov/pub/naif/generic_kernels/spk/satellites/plu017xl.bsp

 

Those files need to be copied to the application data directory. The standard application data directory is different on each platform:

 

In Mac OS X:  ~/Library/Application\ Support/stasb/STA/spice/

 

In Windows XP: C:\Documents and Settings\<user_name>\Local Settings\Application Data\stasb\STA\spice

 

In Windows 7: C:\Users\<user_name>\Application Data\stasb\STA\spice

 

Understanding where STA files are located in your system after installation

 

The binaries of STA along with required pre-compiled libraries are stored under any folder the user may choose. For example:

* In Windows, the installer offers the user to install under “C:\Program Files\STA”

* In Linux, the installer offers the user to install under “/usr/local/STA”

* In MAC OS X, the installer offers the user to install under “/Applications”

 

To function properly, STA requires some extra data files that are grouped in a particular folder. This folder contains start-up scripts of STA, textures of planets and moons, spacecraft 3D models, etc.

* In Windows, the installer will install the data folder under “C:\Program Files\STA\sta-data”

* In Linux, the installer will install the data folder under “/usr/local/STA/sta-data”

* In MAC OS X, the binary application contains already the required data inside the bundle.

 

While you can change the location of the STA binaries, you need to change the location of the data files with the binary. Otherwise, STA will report and error at run time.

 

 

USING STA

 

Once, STA is run for the first time, the next screen appears to the user.

 

 

 

The main screen contains 5 areas:

* The SCENARIO VIEW area. This area allows to add and remove all the elements that form part of a given scenario. The sum of all elements for the current scenario view.

* The SCENARIO ELEMENT BOX area. This area contains all allowable elements of a given scenario, like spacecraft, ground stations,

* The GRAPHICS VIEW area. This area displays 2D and 2D trajectory visualisations of the elements that contain the scenario.

* The TIME-LINE area. This area displays and controls the time of live of the elements of the scenario. It allows to play back the movement of the spacecraft in the scenario.

* The 2D and 3D CONTROLS area controls certain visualisation features of the 2D and 3D rendering area.

 

Docking and Un-docking Windows

In STA all working areas mentioned earlier can be docked and un-docked from the main rendering area. This feature allows the use to maximise the screen real state when concentrating on a particular area or type of work.

 

To undock an area from the main rendering area it is enough to click twice on the upper frame (banner) of the area the user wishes to undock. It is also possible to undock an area by clicking on the undock icon

 

To dock back the undocked area to its original position, it is sufficient to click twice on the  upper frame (banner) of the area the user wishes to dock back.

 

The rendering area undocks in a different manner: the user must explicitly click on the pull-down menu “Undock Ground Track View”. This produces the undock of the 2D view window from the 3D view window. To dock back the window, the user must click again on the pull down menu “Dock Ground Track View”.

 

 

WORKING WITH SPACE SCENARIOS

Understanding the Space Scenario Concept in STA

STA implements the concept of Space Scenario Paradigm (SSP). The SSP of the STA software suite implements the central idea of scenario in which elements can interact to allow the user detailed analysis of these elements.

 

STA defines the concept of Space Scenario (SS) as “a set of elements that play a role in the analysis of trajectory path in a given Universe”.

 

Following the previous definition, the components of a Space Scenario could be active participants (e.g. spacecraft, ground stations, sensors etc.) and also planets, aerodynamics database of a vehicle, co-ordinate systems, etc.

 

Every participant is composed of active and non-active elements and they are divided in two big groups:

* Ground elements (like launch pads, ground stations, points, etc)

* Space Vehicles (like satellites, rockets, re-entry vehicles, etc)

 

Ground elements are characterised by a ground position and a central body.

 

Space Vehicles are characterised by:

* Trajectory plan, a set of trajectories which model the entire life of the element. In every trajectory the user needs to specify all the information needed to define its evolution uniquely in space and time.

* Payload set, a set of payloads which model the entire payload assembly of the vehicle. In every payload the user needs to specify all the information needed to define its features uniquely.

 

The Space Scenario Paradigm is implemented using XML descriptions. XML is an extensible markup language which easily permits to describe the tree structure of the scenario. Every XML file has to be validated by an XML Schema which define the constraints on the structure and content of documents of that type.

 

Creating, Saving, and Loading Scenarios

To create from scratch a new scenario, the user must click on the pull-down menu “File -> New Scenario”.

 

STA responds by creating a new scenario with an empty scenario view.

 

Next, the user needs to place some participants in our new scenario. To do this, the user needs to drag a participant from the Scenario Element area (box) and drop it on top of the word “Scenario” in the Scenario View area. STA responds by creating a new participant.

 

Our scenario contains now a single participant. To be able to calculate a trajectory the user needs to drag and drop a mission arc into our participant.  

 

At this point in time, the user is now ready to edit the properties of the trajectory arc. Clicking twice on the trajectory arc in the Scenario View area, the user can edit the properties of this mission arc.

 

More participants can be introduced now in our scenario. Simply drag and drop any of the participants icons on the word “Scenario”.

 

Saving an scenario is easily done using the STA pull-down menus: File -> Save as

 

All STA scenarios must have the file extension *.stas

 

STA will not recognise any scenario file with a different file extension.

 

Loading a previously saved scenario is also easily done using the STA pull-down menus: File -> Open scenario

 

STA comes with several examples prepared for the user. Look into the STA data folder for a sub-folder name “scenario-examples”.

 

Among all possible CAMBRIAN participants, STA allows ground stations to be placed on a given scenario. CAMBRIAN however, allows the user to select a particular set of ground stations: the ESTRACK ESA and the NASA networks. The ESTRACK network is the set of tracking stations of the European Space Agency. The location of these stations on Earth has been predefined in STA so the user does not need to introduce this information when creating a new participant ground station.

 

The user can include a new ESTRACK or NASA ground station on a given scenario by dragging and dropping the station icon on the word “Scenario”. After the user has placed the new station it will render on the 2D view window once the user run a “propagation” (see more on propagating on the next section).

 

Propagating Trajectories in STA

Once the trajectory plan data of a particular space vehicle has been entered into STA, the user must “propagate” the trajectory. This is performed by means of the STA pull-down menu “Propagate” of by entering the keystrokes <Ctr+P> (Windows and Linux) or <Command+P> (MAC).

 

STA will respond by propagating the trajectory and creating the necessary files that will contain the history of the state vectors of the space vehicle concerned.

 

The ephemeris files generated after the propagation are placed on the root of the STA data folder.

 

STA 2D View: Ground Tracks

Any propagated trajectory will be immediately displayed by STA on the rendering area in 2D view. The 2D view is a Miller projection of the ground track of the calculated trajectory.

STA 3D View: Orthogonal Trajectories

When the user calculates a trajectory and this is rendered on the 2D view as a ground track, STA also displays the trajectory on the 3D view immediately as a orthogonal view.

 

 

Controlling the camera in the 3D view

The mouse and arrow keys are used to control the camera in STA's 3D window. Some of the controls operate with respect to an origin object, which may be set by right clicking on an object of interest.

Mouse controls

Left drag mouse: orbit the current origin object

Right drag mouse: pan the camera

Shift+mouse move: orbit the current origin object (equivalent to left drag)

Alt+mouse move: pan the camera (equivalent to right drag)

Mouse wheel: zoom in and out from the current origin object

 

The alt and shift move controls are provided mainly for laptop users, as it can be inconvenient to hold and drag on a trackpad.

 

Arrow keys

Up / down: pitch the camera

Left / right: roll the camera

 

Context menu

The context menu is activated by right clicking on an object in the 3D view. On Macs without two button mice, you can activate the context menu by holding the control key when you click the mouse

 

Arrows and axes

The first group of options in the context menu controls the visibility of arrows and axes. The arrows are scaled to be about twice the radius of whatever object they're attached to.

 

To show body axes: Show axes for the body-fixed frame of the selected object. The x, y, and z axes are colored red, green, and blue, respectively.

 

To show frame axes: Show axes for the reference frame in which the body's attitude is defined. The x, y, and z axes are colored red, green, and blue, respectively. The frame axes are drawn partially translucent in order to make them distinguishable from the body axes.

 

To show velocity direction: Show the direction of the velocity with respect to the current central body (e.g. the Earth, for an Earth-orbiting satellite.)

 

To show Earth direction: Show an arrow pointing in the direction of the Earth. The Earth direction arrow is light blue.

 

To show Sun direction: Show an arrow pointing in the direction of the Sun. The Sun direction arrow is light yellow.

 

Observer frame

The second group of options in the context menu controls the reference frame of the observer, or camera. Selecting any of these options will set the observer's origin object to the clicked object. Additionally, the observer reference frame will be set as follows:

 

Centered observer: sets the origin object and makes the observer reference frame inertial.

 

Fixed observer: sets the observer reference frame to the body-fixed frame of the selected object.

 

Rotating observer: set the observer's reference frame to the co-rotating frame of the selected object and its central body.

 

STA Time-Lines

The “Time-Line” area allows the user to control the movement of the space vehicles on a given scenario by playing-back a previously propagated session with space vehicles, ground stations, etc.

 

The time-line displays a set of bars in different colours. Each bar corresponds to a space vehicle.

 

The lower left part of the time-line area contains the playback controls of the simulation.

The controls allow the user to “play”, “accelerate”, “retard”, or “play backwards” the movement of the space vehicles in the scenario along the time-line simulation.

 

The lower right part of the time-line area contains the zoom controls of the simulation time-line.

The zoom allows the user to enlarge or shorten a given time line by effectibly zoom it in and out. This provides a good tool to observe the granularity of a given simulation time-line.

 

 

Communications and Coverage Module

This chapter describes all the capabilities of the Coverage Module of STA and how to use them. The Coverage Module is in charge of setting up the coverage and communications features of payloads of participants on a given scenario.

 

In order to simulate a proper transmission, the spacecraft must be orbiting around a planet of making any type of movement. The mission plan must be filled up.

 

When creating a payload set, the user can choose between several payload types:

 

 

 

 

The functions that belong to the Coverage Module are performed by the Transmitter and the Receiver payloads. The user can drag and drop these elements to the Payload Set area of a spacecraft or a ground station.

 

STA allows the user to place several transmitters and several receivers in the same participant. Thus, the user is able to configure different antennas to simulate transmissions in different frequency bands, etc.

 

Transmitter GUI

There are three GUIs the user must set up. There will be default values for each parameter in case the user does not want to input them. The first GUI is the Transmitter:

The first tab of the transmitter called Features represents the parameters of an antenna. The frequency for the transmission and the efficiency of the antenna are gathered in the Antenna Properties area. With this two parameters and one of the parameters of the Antenna Size Options area, the rest of the values are calculated. Actually, there are just two types of beam: omnidirectional and parabolic. When the user chooses the omnidirectional beam, the Antenna Size Options Area is disables (due to theoretically, an omnidirectional antenna has no gain in any direction for being isotropic).

 

The second tab is the Transmitter parameters.

 

This second tab allows the user to input the transmitting power, the definition of the equipment through losses of the feeder (transmission line between the antenna and the receiver), de-pointing losses, polarisation, modulation, etc.

 

Receiver GUI

The first tab (Features) is common for the Transmitter and the Receiver GUI

This GUI allows the user to model a receiver. The user shall be able to input the polarisation of the receiver, a constant antenna temperature or a calculated one, parameters in order to calculate the System Temperature, etc. TA link budget takes into account many parameters: the transmitting power, the gain of the transmitting antenna, the gain of the receiving, free space losses, atmospheric attenuation, polarisation losses, etc. For instance, if the user sets a linear polarisation for the transmitter and a right-handed circular polarisation for the receiver, this shall cause some decibels of attenuation. The user must care about this issues (the same frequency, the same bandwidth...) if he wants an excellent transmission. However, the Coverage Module gives the possibility of modelling several attenuations and losses.

 

The third and last GUI allows the user to choose wether the simulation shall take into account atmospheric effects or not. The user, just clicking checkboxes, is able to choose which atmospheric effect is going to be simulated. The rain model allows him to input the percentage of time of an average year in which the estimated attenuation is exceeded. By default there is a value of 0.01%.

Once all these GUIs are configured, the user shall propagate the scenario and use the Analysis Module in order to get reports, plots. In order to propagate the scenario, as it was said before, the user must click in the menu Calculate/Propagate.

 

Analyzing coverage

To analyze any coverage of a given payload, the user must click on the menu Tools => Analysis.

 

First of all, the simulation time must be chosen. In order to do this, the user shall click on the mission arc of the spacecraft and then click default (or choose another simulation time). Then, the user must choose the transmitter and receiver involved in the simulation.

 

There are several parameters that can be use to analyze a given mission. For the Coverage analysis, the azimuth, range and elevation are automatically calculated. These values represent the relative position from the ground station to the spacecraft.

 

The communication parameters are related to the link budget calculations. These are the  possible parameters: Equivalent Isotropic Radiated Power, Received Frequency, Doppler Shift, Received, Power, Flux Density, Overlap Band width factor, Free Space Loss, Oxygen Loss, Water Vapour Loss, Atmospheric Loss, Rain Loss, Propagation Loss, G/T, C/N0, C/N, Eb/N0, BER.

 

ENTRY

This chapter describes all the functionalities of STA Entry (some times called Re-Entry) Module as an integrated STA module; as due to its integration in STA some features of the module have been modified, this document aims to help the user simulating re-entry trajectories.

Calculating a Re-entry trajectory

The procedure that must be followed by the user when trying to simulate a re-entry trajectory is the following:

* Open a new scenario;

* Add a re-entry vehicle to the scenario by dragging and dropping the correspondent icon to the scenario tree item;

* Add a re-entry trajectory to the re-entry vehicle by dragging the correspondent icon to the trajectory plan item;

* Supply the GUI with the proper parameters;

* Click the propagate button in Calculate menu.

 

 

The user should also specify the following values in the (aerodynamic and physical) properties GUI:

* Mass value : is the vehicle mass value; a default value of 1000 kg is already set in the S/C Mass box. A mass equal to zero will generate an error message when propagating;

* Radius base : a radius base equal to zero will generate an error message when propagating

* Radius nose : this value should be set when the user wants to perform a thermal analysis of the re-entry trajectory; a radius nose equal to zero will not generate an error message and will not influence the trajectory.

* CD coefficients: the user shall write the name of the file that contains the vehicle CD coefficients (without considering the parachute if existing); the user can also find the file in the system by clicking on the button “Load file”. The file name should not include the path. If the user wants to load an external file, he shall include that file in the STA folder \sta-data\data\aerodynamics. A Cd coefficients file name not existing (i.e. not in the \sta-data\data\aerodynamics folder) or an empty case will generate an error message when propagating. The Cd coefficients file should imperatively be a .stad file with the following structure: First column is the ALTITUDE [km], and the second column is the CD coefficients [-]

* G load limit: the user shall insert the maximum value of the G Load; as the simulation will stop when this value is reached, the user shall take into account the possible influence of a low value on the trajectory propagation. A G load limit value equal to zero will generate an error message.

Heat rate limit : the user shall insert the maximum value of the SP heat rate; as the simulation will stop when this value is reached, the user shall take into account the possible influence of a low value on the trajectory propagation. A SP heat rate equal to zero will generate an error message.

* CD parachute coefficients: the user shall write the name of the file that contains the vehicle CD only parachute coefficients. The user can also find the file in the system by clicking on the button “Load file”. The file name should not include the path. If the user wants to load an external file, he shall include that file in the STA folder \sta-data\data\aerodynamics. A Cd parachute coefficients file name not existing (i.e. not in the \sta- data\data\aerodynamics folder) or an empty case will generate an error message when propagating. The Cd parachute coefficients file should imperatively be a .stad file with the same structure of the Cd coefficients file. Even if the vehicle is not supplied with a parachute, the user shall specify a file name for the Cd parachute coefficients (in order to avoid an error message); to nullify its influence on the propagation it is enough to set the parachute surface value and/or the deployment  Mach number value equal to zero.

* Parachute surface: the user shall insert the parachute surface value; a value equal to zero will not generate an error message.

* Deployment Mach number: the user shall insert the parachute deployment Mach number value; a value equal to zero will not generate an error message.

 

As regards with the re-entry GUI, the values the user shall insert are the following:

* Starting epoch: the user shall specify the initial time of the simulation; default time is J2000 reference time.

* Coordinate system type : the user shall choose between 3 types of coordinates systems; the initial orbital state window will automatically change accordingly to his choice. The default type is keplerian coordinates;

* Initial orbital state: the user shall specify the initial state of the spacecraft; depending on the inserted values the trajectory could be a re-entry trajectory or the simulation could stop immediately or after some time.

* Central body: the user shall select the central body between Earth and Mars; default body is Earth.

* Atmosphere Model: the user shall select from the list the atmosphere model he intends to use; the default model is gram-99.

* Gravity model, zonal and tesseral boxes: these inputs are not active yet (they will be after the perturbations layer development)

* Integrator type: this mode is not active (it will be after the integrators box development)

* Integration step: the user shall select the integration step value; a value equal to zero will generate a message error.

 

 

Analysis Module

This chapter will describe the functionalities of the Analysis Module, as a tool of STA. The Analysis Module is responsible for analysing all the data that can be calculated by the different modules of STA, according to the user's specifications and needs. The AM can be called whenever a propagation has occurred, by clicking on “Analysis” in the “Tools” menu of the STA main window.

 

 

There are several areas in the GUI: the analysis format, the scenario, the time intervals, the list of available parameters, the parameters to include in the analysis, and the parameters per axis. A brief explanation on the different areas is provided below.

 

 

The analysis format: the user can select which output he/she wishes to produce: 2D plot, 3D plot, or text report; according to the selected format, the GUI changes showing the report or the plotting options.

 

The scenario: a copy of the scenario tree is displayed in the GUI.

 

Time intervals: list of different time intervals that can be used in the analysis; only the selected intervals will be considered.

 

List of available parameters: it exists in the report option and contains all the list of the parameters that can be calculated by the Analysis Module, organized according to field (Coverage, Analysis, Aerodynamics, etc).

 

Parameters to include in the analysis:  it exists in the report option and contains a list of all the parameters that will appear in the report, according to the order by which they were selected; the user can specify the coordinate systems and the units in which the parameters shall be displayed

 

Parameters per axis: it exists in any of the plotting option and consists on a list of all the available parameters to be calculated by the Analysis Module; the user must select the one that shall appear in that axis (x, y or z).

 

Analyzing a mission

The user must select the type of output that he/she wishes to have (text report or plot), in the analysis format area.

 

In the Time intervals area, the user must insert one or more time intervals during which the analysis shall be performed. There are several functionalities available in this area: the user can select one or more mission arcs from the scenario tree in the GUI of the AM and press “Default”. In this way, the time of all the selected missions is added to the Time intervals area. It is important to notice that all the items selected in the scenario must be valid mission arcs, otherwise no time intervals will be added to the list. The time intervals can be user-specified by pressing the “New” button; 2 pop-up windows will appear: one to define the start epoch and another to define the stop epoch; the format of the time and date shall be the one that is in the pop-up windows, otherwise a warning message will appear when the “Generate” button is pressed. Any time interval from the list can be deleted by selecting the item and pressing “Delete” before performing any analysis the user must select one or more time intervals from the list; only the selected time intervals will be considered and in case no   interval is selected, a warning message will appear and the analysis will not be  performed.

If the selected times correspond to intervals outside the propagation interval for each mission arc, no data is displayed and a warning message appears. The time step of the analysis is the same time step that the user specifies in the mission arc properties.

 

The Report Option

The user must select the parameters that shall be included in the area “Parameters to include in the analysis”. The coordinate system and the units in which the results shall be displayed can be selected from the lists that appear in front of the name of each parameter. The report is generated by pressing the “Generate” button and will automatically open in a new window.

 

The Plotting Option

The user must select one parameter to appear in each axis of the plot: one parameter in the x and y axes, for the 2D plot and one parameter for the x, y, and z axes for the 3D plot. Only one parameter per axis is supported for the time being, which means that no multiple plots are available. Unlike the Report, the plotting tool of the Analysis Module only supports one time interval, which means that there are no discontinuities in the plotted data. It is important to to notice that some parameters are not available to plot, in this case, a warning message appears saying the selected options to plot are not valid. This happens for some time formats, such as the Gregorian formats and the YYDDD. Only the parameters that are numbers (without text or symbols like “/” or “-”) are considered to be plotted. The plot will appear in a separate window by pressing the “Generate” button.

 

System's Engineering

This module allows the user to conduct a preliminary system engineering analysis out of a given satellite participant.

 

 

The procedure that must be followed by the user when trying to perform a system engineering analysis is the following:

* Open a new scenario;

* Add one or more satellite to the scenario by dragging and dropping the correspondent icon to the scenario tree item;

* Add, if wanted, some inputs to the satellite properties GUI;

* Click the system engineering button in Calculate menu.

* Choose in the list in the new dialog window the satellite for whom the system engineering analysis will be performed.

 

 

STA Perturbations Service

In this chapter an overview of this service layer will be given in order to let the user understand the potential and possible applications for this STA components. Therefore a general explanation of the Perturbations Layer will be given as well as an introduction to the main features. The most used model for trajectories design is the 2-body problem, where a satellite, with negligible mass, is gravitating around a central body.

 

The propagation of this kind of orbit, when only the central body's influence is considered, can be easily done by incrementing the true anomaly at each time step when keeping constant all the other orbital parameters, obtaining the exact solution. This operation is done by the Loitering Module.

However this kind of trajectories are only theoretical, because this simple model is complicated by the effects of orbital perturbations (generated by different causes), that exert a perturbing acceleration on the spacecraft (the magnitude of these accelerations is some degree smaller with respect to the acceleration due to central body attraction).

 

Introducing the orbital perturbation implies the necessity to solve a differential equation for the calculation of the spacecraft position and velocity at each time step.

 

The orbital perturbations that have been treated by the layer are :

Aerodynamic drag due to the central body's atmosphere;

Solar pressure radiation perturbation;

Gravity of the third body perturbation;

Central body's gravity field perturbation;

Debris and micrometeorids collisions perturbation.

 

Adding one or more of these perturbations allows solving the equations of motion taking into account these perturbing factors.  Not only the Loitering trajectory can be influenced by perturbations: theoretically all kinds of trajectory, from re-entry to rendez-vous, are affected by perturbations, but in certain cases the perturbing effects are so small compared to the main forces acting on the spacecraft that they can be ignored without committing significant errors.

This is the reason why, while in the Loitering module it will be possible to add all the perturbations listed above, in the REM only the central body's gravity field perturbation can be added; moreover, in the REM the aerodynamic drag will not be treated as a perturbation but as the main force acting on the spacecraft.

 

Using the Perturbations Layer

As explained in the previous paragraph, the user shall use the Perturbations Layer when he wants to simulate a trajectory considering the effects of orbital perturbations; the inputs related to perturbations will be added in a dedicate tab contained in the GUI of the specific trajectory he wants to propagate.

 

On a given mission arc, the user must  open the tab “Environment”. He can firstly select the central body from the menu and then pass to the “Perturbations” section. Here the selection of the perturbations wanted to be taken into account in the propagation shall be made by clicking the radio button associated to every perturbation; when selecting it, the corresponding field enables and the user can insert in it some other values, when possible.

 

Aerodynamic drag due to the central body's atmosphere is activated when the clicking  on “Atmospheric Drag”. The inputs to be inserted are the following:

* Atmospheric model : it refers to a file containing a list of densities as function of the altitudes, necessary for the calculation of the atmosphere effect on the spacecraft. The user can choose from a list of models; so far the models are: gram99 (Global Reference Atmospheric Model), exponential model, based on the simple exponential formula for density calculation, USSA1976 (U.S. Standard Atmosphere 1976), mars_emcd (European Mars Climate Database)

Solar pressure radiation perturbation: the button to be clicked is “Solar Pressure”. The inputs to be inserted are the following: reflectivity : it refers to the reflectivity constant of the surface of the spacecraft; the user shall insert a number from 0 to 1 (0 : no reflectivity, 1 : completely reflective), Albedo : the user shall select this case if he wants to simulate the albedo radiation from the central body, IR : the user shall select this case if he wants to simulate the infra-red radiation from the central body.

* Central body's gravity field perturbation: the button to be clicked is “Gravity Field”. The inputs to be inserted are the following: gravity model (it refers to a file containing a list of harmonic coefficients representing the potential of the gravity field depending on the actual shape of the celestial body), gravity tesserals (it represents the number of tesseral harmonics the user wants to take into account in the simulation where the higher the number, better the approximation of the gravity perturbation).

* Gravity of the third body perturbation: the button to be clicked is “Third Body”. The inputs to be inserted are the following: Once decided which celestial bodies will be considered as exerting an influence on the spacecraft, select them from the list on the left and put them in the list on the right by double-clicking them.

 

Every file refers to a particular central body; the available models are: EGM2008 (Earth Gravitational Model 2008), GTM090 (Mars Gravity Model deducted from Mars Global Surveyor mission), SHGJ180 (Venus Gravity Model deducted from Magellan mission), JGL165 (Moon Gravity Model deducted from Lunar Prospector mission, see).

 

The gravity zonals represent the number of zonal harmonics the user wants to take into account in the simulation: higher the number, better the approximation of the gravity perturbation. The user can put a integer from 2 to 20.

 

The debris and micrometeoroids collisions perturbation is activated when the button “MMOD” is clicked. There are no inputs to be added.

 

Re-entry Aerodynamics Module

STA provides the capability of generating aerodynamic coefficients from a user-defined geometry file as an alternative to giving the aerodynamic coefficients files directly. The models that have been implemented for this generation of coefficients are local inclination methods similar to those which are used in the Supersonic/Hypersonic Arbitrary Body Program (S/HABP). Results should be treated with caution, as these methods should be considered to give results useful in a conceptual design stage.

This chapter of the manual will give an overview of the capabilities of the Re-entry Aerodynamics Module (RAM) and how to exploit these capabilities using STA. First the geometry file format will e elaborated upon, followed by an overview of the parametrized geometries available in STA. Subsequently, the aerodynamic coefficient generation and aerodynamic method selection are discussed.

 

Geometry file format

This section will give a description of the Langley Wireframe Geometry Standard (LaWGS), a computer standard for defining a wireframe geometry, with the file extension .wgs. The geometry format bases the definition of the wireframe on a discrete number of points which make up an object, the entire configuration can then be defined from an arbitrary number of these objects. Objects may be defined in a (right-handed Cartesian) global coordinate system, or a local coordinate system, where a specification of the translation, rotation and scaling from the local to global coordinate system must be specified.

 

Each object is made up of a number of contour lines, where each contour lines is made up out of a number of points, the connection between which forms the contour. The number of contours and points per contour may be chosen by the user, but must be consistent throughout an object, so that all contours have the same amount of points. This is not required for different objects, though. Additionally, the description must be consistent, so that all contours are defined in the same order i.e. (counter-)clockwise. For programs which use paneling methods, such as S/HABP, the formation of panel surface normals from the wireframe is not uniquely defined, as a normal may be pointing in- or outwards. To retain consistency, two main types of geometries and an associated recommended manner of defining them in LaWGS are used, 'fusiform' and 'planar' objects. Fusiform objects, such as a fuselage or engine nacelle, should contain contour lines starting at the nose and ending at the rear, with the first point on each line the one with lowest z-location and successive points given in a clockwise manner (when viewed from the front). For planar bodies, such as wings or tails, the contour should start at the trailing edge and should contain be ordered so that the bottom comes first on the contour.

 

The .wgs file should be built up in the following manner, with each string of text enclosed in single quotes. Separators that are allowed are blanks, commas and slashes, with additional blanks before or after separators allowed:

 

Line 1: Configuration name.

 

The following three should be repeated for each object in the configuration.

Line 2: Object Name.

Line 3: Object Number, Number of lines, Number of points per contour line, local symmetry identifier (see below), Rotation angles around X,Y,Z axes, translation along X,Y,Z axes, scaling factor in X,Y,Z, direction, global symmetry identifier.

Line 4: X,Y,Z coordinates for the object's constituent points. First all sets of points on first contour line (in order), then of the second, etc. An enter may be used after each point or contour for readability.

 

The rotation and translation and scaling values should be separated and are used to transform from the local to the global coordinate system. If the two coincide, this series should be 0,0,0,0,0,0,1,1,1 (when using commas as separators).

Symmetry identifiers are as follows:

 

 0: not symmetrical

 1: symmetrical about X-Z axis

 2: symmetrical about X-Y axis

 3: symmetrical about Y-Z axis

 

Symmetry operations and going from local to global coordinates is done in the order that the defining values are input (order defined above). An example of the contour lines, as well as the paneled geometry, is given in 11.1.1. Note the difference in contour orientation between the fuselage and the wings, tail and body flap.

 

 

To perform the aerodynamic analysis, the geometry file should be properly created.

 

One important aspect that must be observed is that the vehicle points must be provided in such a manner that the resulting surface normals are outward pointing. The following is an example of what will produce properly oriented normals:

 

When defining the contours from the front to back and viewing the vehicle from the front, the points on the contour should be defined in counter clockwise direction.

 

Furthermore, the following points should be realized when making the geometry file:

For closed contours, the first and last point on this contour should be equal. The RAM does not automatically connect the first and last point on a contour (to allow for both open and closed contours).

 

For the beginning and/or end of a geometry, it is possible that all points on a contour lie on the same point in space. This could occur, for instance, on a fuselage front or a pointed wing tip. Care should be taken to ensure that no single panel has all points in the same position in space as this may result in zero panel area.

 

One point which should be taken into consideration is that shadowing is not yet included in the aerodynamic analysis. This has an impact on the analysis on parts of the vehicle where different vehicle parts overlap. This occurs, for instance, on the wing attachment surface to a fuselage. Currently, if the fuselage is defined as a succession of closed contours, the parts of the fuselage where the wing is attached will not be recognized as 'internal' or 'shaodowed'. A possible fix is to use two open contours instead of one closed contour for the fuselage sections containg a wing attachment. These contours would still require the same number of points as all other contours in the vehicle part, though.

 

Parametrized geometry

Currently four parametrized geometries have been implemented. The geometry files are automatically generated from these parametrizations through the "Geometry generation" GUI. This allows the user to perform entry analyses without providing aerodynanic coefficient of geometry files.

 

 

 

From the combo box 'vehicle type', the vehicle shape can be selected, upon which the parameters that are to be defined are shown in the GUI. Additionally, the user has the freedom to define the number of contours on the vehicle and the number of points per contour. Clicking generate geometry will generate the .wgs file.

Aerodynamic Coefficient Files

The aerodynamic coefficients and related quantities are set from the Aerodynamic Properties GUI. Currently, only quantities related to translational motion can be set. The reference area is set automatically when a parametrized shape is created (but not when the .wgs file of one is loaded). The reference area for parametrized geometries is the base area in the case of the blunted cone and the bi-cone and the disc area based on the mid-radius for the capsule and probe.

 

 

The primary output of the RAM is an aerodynamic database file, which is to be saved in a location specified in the Space Scenario. The format of the file is identical to that used in ASTOS, see [R9]. A short overview of the file will also be given here.

 

The aerodynamic coefficient file first contains n lines, where n is the number of independent variables in the database. Note that no information is available in the file on which variables these are, so that a user should keep proper track of which files have originated where.

 

The aerodynamic coefficients are then provided in a (set of) table(s). If only a single variable is considered, only a single row of values is provided. For two variables, a single table is provided, with the columns corresponding to different values of the 1st variable and the rows the 2nd variable. For a larger number of variables, a separate table is provided for each combination of the remaining variables.

 

Currently, STA only provides the capability use dependancy on Mach number for simulation the trajectory. In this case, the coefficient file consists of two lines of numbers. The first of these lines cotain the Mach numbers at which the coefficients are given, the second line gives the value of the coefficients at these Mach numbers. The RAM code includes functionality for angle of attack and sideslip dependancy, though.

 

STA uses aerodynamic coefficients in wind axes for the use in translational trajectory propagation. It should be stressed that all  aerodynamic forces (and correspondingly the coefficients) are defined to be positive in the direction opposite to the axes. Consequently, the lift is positive in 'upward' direction, the drag in 'backwards' (colinear with velocity vector) direction and the side force completes the right-handed coordinte system. Note that the side force is sometimes defined in the opposite direction and one should be careful when comparing to database values or when manually generating such files.

 

Aerodynamic coefficient generation

Upon clicking the 'Generate Files from Geometry' button in the aerodynamics GUI, a new GUI will be opened.

 

 

The vehicle geometry file that is selected is analysed and each part is shown in the tree widget, with group boxes for each aerodynamic method that can be selected for them. Additionally, the number of contours and the number of points per contour of each part are shown. By setting the aerodynamic methods for each part as desired and pressing the 'Generate geometry' button in the lower right corner, the coefficient files are generated.

 

In addition to this functionality, the aerodynamic methods that are used can be selected automatically. The coefficients that are used by the aerodynamic selection can be tuned by the user by opening the 'Advanced Settings' GUI.

 

In addition, the Aerodynamic coefficient GUI gives a number of additional options:

* Ability to set a 'default' attitude for a 3DOF simulation. By setting this , these default values are used as the attitude throughout the entire simulation. In essence, it sets the single combination of angle of attack and sidelip at which the database is created.

* Ability to generate coefficients in body or wind axes. Although the trajectory simulation takes the force coefficients in wind axes as input, the capability to give coefficients in body axes may be advantageous for comparing to database values from literature.

* Possibility for the user to define whether to use a distinction between the low and high hypersonic regimes for which aerodynamic methods to use on the vehicle parts. In addition, the range of these regimes can be set. The lower bound of the low hypersonic regime is fixed at a Mach number of 3, while the upper bound of the high hypersonic regime is set at a Mach number of 20. For the methods that are used currently by STA aerodynamic coefficients at a Mach number of 20 are almost indistinguishable from those at infinite Mach number. For Mach numbers lower than 3, the methods used can no longer be assumed as approximate models and will return spurious results.

* Pressure distribution on the vehicle may be printed to a file to use in more in-depth analysis or visualization of the analysis. The user must select at which Mach numbers the pressure distribution is/are to be printed.

* Geometric information may be printed to a file for post-processing or visualization purposes. Information that is printed includes the panel areas and normals.

 

Automatic Method Selection

In order to allow for the automatic selection of the local inclination method on each of the objects that make up the vehicle, it might be necessary to modify the given geometry file. This will involve cutting a single object into a number of new objects to allow for the use of a different local inclination method on each object, bypassing the limitation of using a singe method per object in the aerodynamics code. However, the optimum cutting location will be dependent on the vehicle's attitude. For this version, a single 'reference attitude' will be used, for which to determine the cutting location. This reference is 0 degrees of angle of attack and sideslip.

 

A number of definition should be clear before proceeding. For the algorithm that is described, both the points which define the vehicle and the centroid position points of each panel are used. Both these sets of points can be used to define both lateral and longitudinal contours. For consistency, no difference in nomenclature will be used between the fusiform and planar geometries (as is the case when defining 'contour' in the .wgs file).

 

Lateral contours: correspond to contours in .wgs file for fusiform; correspond to contours obtained by connecting the points of  equal index in the contour from the contours in .wgs file for planar case.

 

Longitudinal contours: correspond to contours in .wgs file for planars; correspond to contours obtained by connecting the points of  equal index in the contour from the contours in .wgs file for fusiforms.

 

Centroidal longitudinal and centroidal lateral contours are obtained similarly, only using the centroid positions instead of the vehicle definition point positions.
